  "text": "Assuming that the density of PDGF is the same as that of KGF and noting that the molecular weight of PDGF is around 24 kDa [21], we take P ¼ 4:78 Â 10 À8 g cm À3 . The molecular weight of interleukin-1 was found to be in the range 12-70 kDa [CITATION_1] , and for our simulations we consider the higher value 70 kDa. Assuming that the density of interleukin-1 is also the same as that of KGF, we take i ¼ 1:39 Â 10 À7 g cm À3 . We assume that the densities of the ECM and the fibrin clot are comparable and take both c and r to be 10 À3 g cm À3 , which lies within the range of values previously used in simulations by Namy et al. [CITATION_2] . We also assume that the density of the epidermal layer is similar to that of the dermal layer, and take k to be 10 À3 g cm À3 . Using our assumed value for the molecular weight of interleukin-1, we estimate the random motility coefficient by considering the molecular weight, m, and random motility coefficient, D, for another chemical using [CITATION_3] ; the proliferation of keratinocytes will halve under the influence of TGF-b [CITATION_4] ; interleukin-1 stimulates a 2.5-fold rise in fibroblast proliferation [CITATION_5] , downregulates the production of collagen by fibroblasts by 50 per cent [CITATION_6] and increases the production of KGF by fibroblasts by a factor of 6 [CITATION_7] ; and the presence of keratinocytes decreases the production of TGF-b by a factor of 1.6 [CITATION_8] . We thus set the dimensionless values ). This value was deduced from experiments by Wang et al. [CITATION_9] , where the maximum dilution of TGF-b was 2:5 ng ml À1 . Thus, we take the rate constant of TGF-b production for a given density, f , of fibroblasts to be",
